title: Simple Analytics
shortDescription: We never sell your data. Paid account required.
longDescription: Simple Analytics gives you the analytics you need without invading the privacy of your users, with a clean interface, and simple integration. GDPR, CCPA and, PECR compliant because we don't handle PII data and set no cookies. You will need a paid Simple Analytics subscription. The stats will be visible in your Simple Analytics dashboard (not on CloudFlare).
author: Simple Analytics

events_emails.description: Do you have links to email addresses on your website? Then it could make sense to see how many clicks you get on your mailto links.

advanced_settings_toggle.description: Settings that most customers don't need.
advanced_settings_toggle.title: Advanced settings

allow_url_parameters.description: By default, we collect all UTM parameters (with and without the utm_ prefix) and the ref (which is short for utm_source) parameter. We don't store the rest of the query parameters. But some customers have non-personal data in their query parameters—for example, product-id or article-slug. We allow collecting those parameters as long as they are specified via this setting.
allow_url_parameters.title: Allow extra URL parameters

automated_events.description: You can collect a few different events automatically: outbound links, email clicks, and amount of downloads.
automated_events.title: Add automated events

collect_dnt.description: Collect visits from users who have DNT enabled. DNT is to prevent tracking but we never do. So you are allowed to collect those visits as well. By default we don't collect them.
collect_dnt.title: Collect visits of DNT users

custom_domain.description: We created a CNAME record for you that points from 'simple.yourdomain.com' to 'simpleanalyticsexternal.com'. Enter the full domain including the subdomain 'simple'. After this, make sure to add 'simple.yourdomain.com' to your website settings in the Simple Analytics dashboard.
custom_domain.title: Custom domain

download_extensions.description: Use a list of extensions separated by a comma (e.g.: pdf, csv, docx, xlsx)
download_extensions.placeholder: Fill in extensions separated by a comma (or leave empty for defaults)
download_extensions.title: Sepecify which download links should be tracked

downloads_full_url.title: Use the full URL of the download link instead of only the path as the event name

events_downloads.description: Do you have links to pdf's or other files? Collect the amount of downloads. You can specify the extensions of the files your want to collect downloads for.
events_downloads.title: Collect download clicks automatically

events_emails.description: Do you have links to email addresses on your website? Then it could make sense to see how many clicks you get on your mailto links.
events_emails.title: Collect email clicks automatically

events_outbound.description: Outbound links are basically just links that go to a different website. For example you have a website with a few products listed on them. People pay you for listing those products on your website. Now you want to find a way to track the amount of visitors that go to that website. For this you’ll need outbound events!
events_outbound.title: Collect outbound links automatically

events_use_title.description: A title is what you see when you keep your cursor hovered over your link. If not available we use the URL of the link.
events_use_title.title: Use the title of downloads and outbound links as the event name

hash_mode.description: Check this box when you website uses hashtags (#) for navigation (for example carrd.co websites). If you don't know what this means, leave the box unchecked.
hash_mode.title: Website uses hash navigation

hostname.description: What domain do you want to use? (without www., https://, and trailing slashes)
hostname.title: Hostname

ignore_metrics.description: Add the metric you do not want to collect in a comma separated list. For example: referrer,utm,country,session,timeonpage,scrolled,useragent,screensize,viewportsize,language
ignore_metrics.title: Metrics to ignore

ignore_metrics_toggle.description: Our script does only collect non-personal data. But some customers might want to limit our metrics even more. That's why we created the ignore metrics feature.
ignore_metrics_toggle.title: Ignore metrics

ignore_pages.description: Our script does only collect non-personal data. But some customers might want to limit our metrics even more. That's why we created the ignore metrics feature.
ignore_pages.title: Ignore pages

namespace.description: If you don't want to use the default namespace (sa in sa_event), you can update it here.
namespace.title: Namespace

non_unique_hostnames.description: Suppose you redirect your visitors to a payment provider, and after they complete the payment, they return to your website. Because of the nature of not tracking visitors in Simple Analytics, we count those “returning” visitors as new visitors. To prevent this from happening, you can specify the hostname of that payment provider to tell us we should register this visit as non-unique.
non_unique_hostnames.title: Non unique hostnames

outbound_full_url.title: Use the full URL of outbound links instead of only the path as the event name.

overwrite_hostname.description: Do you want to overwrite the domain name of this website?
overwrite_hostname.title: Overwrite hostname

overwrite_namespace.description: If you don't want to use the default namespace (sa in sa_event), you can update it.
overwrite_namespace.title: Overwrite namespace

strict_utm.description: When collecting UTM codes, we allow to skip the utm_ part. In our dashboard utm_source, source, ref will be stored as utm_source. But sometimes both parameters are used. To give you control over which parameter we should store you can enable strict UTMs. After that only UTM codes with the utm_ prefix will work.
strict_utm.title: Enable Strict UTMs

use_custom_domain.description: If you have a custom subdomain you can enable it here
use_custom_domain.title: Use your custom domain

use_events.description: If you want to add events to your code you can enble them here. We will make sure the sa_event function is available.
use_events.title: Use events
